Q9: Collaboration happens best not only when everyone gets to properly voice their opinion, but when everyone else properly understands the opinions being presented. It also requires being open to providing and taking feedback not as a personal attack, but as a constructive process to make the end product better for everyone.
Q10: No one really understands the ideas being presented by others. Feedback is presented or taken aggressively or as a personal attack, resulting in no significant progress towards a final goal being made--also making the group feel like a us vs. them situation instead of a unified front against a problem. Even worse if no communication is happening at all, likely resulting in a total disconnect between all the work being done and producing a final product which is clearly not greater than the sum of its parts.
Q11: I generally try to rise to a leadership position in situations where poor collaboration is occurring to recommend ways to improve the collaboration to be more efficient and to most effectively tackle the given problem. This includes providing a clear plan of attack, outlining clear roles and responsibility, agreeing upon straightforward communication guidelines, and regularly checking in with individuals and stakeholders to ensure work is progressing as intended towards the desired solution. If I can't lead, I just try to communicate as best I can with those related to my task and complete the work in the gaps which dynamically appear during group collaboration.
Q13:
Communication is king. Communicating what you know efficiently and clearly is a skill you should master to work effectively with others. You could solve all the world's problems, but if no one else understands the solutions, they're useless. 
Clear, actionable deliverables on a well-documented timeline agreed upon and regularly updated by all parties is one of the most effective ways to resolve any problem efficiently. 
There is power in playing into your strengths and acknowledging your weaknesses. A team of people doing what they do best will be infinitely more effective than a group of people arbitrarily assigned to tasks.
Q14:
Don't be afraid to step in and lead a room, but never force you way to the top. If someone else is already clearly leading without issue, trying to step up will just introduce clashes and awkward power dynamics. 
Give and take all advice as feedback on your work, not on you as a person. If someone says your work is trash, that doesn't mean *you* are trash. Likewise, if someone else's work *is* trash, call it out. Don't let bad work go into a finished product just because you were too afraid to call it out. In some fields, that could even put lives on the line. 
Never be afraid to learn more. If someone says something that doesn't make sense to you, don't just ignore it and don't arbitrarily challenge it. Ask questions. Understand their reasoning. Maybe they just didn't think it through, maybe they don't have a fundamental understanding of the problem, or maybe they do and you learn something new.
Q51: How much of the project can they actually explain all the way down to the fundamentals why certain choices were made. Someone who just exists in a group can tell you what the outcome to a problem was, but only someone who was doing the work of solving the problem can tell you every intricate detail of what issues came up and how exactly it was solved. Details--this is the same for technical interviews.
Q52: Does the final product look like a collection of separate projects stitched together arbitrarily, or are all the components seamlessly integrated together. A smart group of people can all solve their own problems extremely well, but unless they're collaborating effectively as a group, their final product will look like just that--a collection of solutions instead of one unified solution.
